Pt reports that middle of this past week she started getting SOB 
with exertion. Denies cough, fevers, chills, night sweats, 
weight changes, chest pain, ___ swelling, wheezing over that 
time. She gets dialysis ___ and then was 
scheduled for an extra session today (sat) due to the DOE and 
hope that taking off extra vlume would help. Her symptoms here 
were worse afterwards and she complained of lightheadedness, 
dizziness, feeling very weak. Found to have BP of 80/50 and 
brought to the ED. No chest pain at any point or pain in neck 
arm back or jaw. No Lower extremity pain or swelling. She does 
not make urine

In the ED, initial VS were: 98.5 69 82/40 20 100%. Briefly on 
peripheral pressors and given small fluid bolus. Pressors 
quickly titrated off. Attempt made to palce IJ but unable to 
thread wire and pt reporting history of central venous clots. 
Trop found to be above baseline (0.15-0.25) at 0.43 so 
cardiology was consulted. In setting of no cardiac symptoms and 
unchanged EKG, they recommended getting CK and CKMB with no 
further workup if not elevated as likely mild stress trop leak 
in setting of lowish BPs. CK/CKMB were flat. R Groin Line is 
dialysis access and this was accessed in the ED. Got CTA before 
went to floor which showed no PE and no evidence of lung 
paranchyma abnormalities. 
 
On arrival to the MICU, BP stable in ___ systolic. Pt reports 
baseline BP around 100 systolic. Comfortable, no increased RR or 
WOB. No longer lightheaded/dizzy. Complains of baseline chronic 
headache.

Brief Hospital Course:
___ w/ HIV (off and on HAART, currently off, last CD4 ___,000 copies/ml on ___ also with ESRD on HD, and presenting 
w/ ___ days of gradual onset SOB of unclear etiology and 
hypotension that seems to be ___ fluid taken off by extra HD 
session. 

# Hypotension:  It was likely that the patient's hypotension 
occurred in the setting of taking off too much volume at HD.  
The patient was in the low ___ on arrival to ED, initially 
admitted to the MICU and was briefly on pressors with lactate 
initially of 4.2.  She improved quickly with a small fluid bolus 
and soon titrated off pressors.  The patient received one dose 
of vanc/zosyn in the ED out of concern for infectious etiology, 
but infectious work up in the MICU was all negative.  On 
transfer from the MICU to the ward, the patient continued to 
remain normotensive.  She was continued on her home dialysis 
schedule.   

# shortness of breath:  The etiology of the patient's shortness 
of breath is unclear.  She was ruled out for PE with CTA, and 
there were no signs or symptoms of heart failure.  The patient 
had elevated LDH in the setting of low CD4 count; however, she 
reports taking her Bactrim ppx and was never hypoxic, making PCP 
very unlikely.  An ECHO was done to evaluate for any underlying 
pulmonary hypertension which was remarkable for ASD and mild MR. 
 ___ that the patient's shortness of breath was in the 
setting of being volume overloaded and did resolve after her 
initial HD session, but then led to resultant hypotension after 
taking off too much fluid.  Upon discharge, the patient was not 
having any shortness of breath.   

# Elevated LDH: The patient was noted to have elevated LDH and 
in the setting of having a borderline calcium, elevated 
eosinophils, and relatively new thrombocytopenia, the work up 
for lymphoma/malignancy was started while the patient was in the 
intensive care unit.  An u/s was done showing a borderline 
increased spleen compared to a study from ___.  The 
patient was also found to have elevated B2 microglobulin, IgG 
and IgM, and PEP was c/w polyclonal hypergammaglobulinemia.   

# Thrombocytopenia: The patient has new thrombocytopenia since 
___.  Her platelets were trended during this admission. 
Uncler etiolgy, but could be secondary to bone marrow 
suppression in the setting of her active HIV disease.  

# ESRD on HD: The patient was continued on her home MWF HD 
schedule while in patinet.  She was continued on her home 
cinacalcet and sevelamer, which was increased at discharge. 

# HIV: The patient is not taking her HAART medications, with 
last CD4 of ___,000 copies/ml on ___.  The patient 
was not started on HAART while in patient, as she has not been 
taking the medications at home.  She was continued on her 
Bactrim and Azithro ppx, which she reports taking at home.  The 
patient has follow up with her ID doctor, ___.  

Transitional Issues:
- The patient was found to have elevated B2 microglobulin, IgG 
and IgM, and PEP was c/w polyclonal hypergammaglobulinemia.  
This will need to be followed up as an oupatient.     

- The patient had ECHO which was notable for ASD and mild MR.  

- The patient is currently not taking her HAART.

radiology.text:
INDICATION:  ___ woman with shortness of breath and hypotension,
question infiltrate.

COMPARISON:  Multiple chest radiographs, the latest from ___,
along the earliest from ___.

ONE VIEW OF THE CHEST:

The lungs are well expanded and clear.  The cardiomediastinal silhouette and
hilar contours are normal.  No pleural effusion or pneumothorax is present.  A
right inferior catheter terminating in the right atrium is slightly lower in
position compared to the previous exam.

IMPRESSION:  No acute intrathoracic process.

HISTORY:  ___ female with hypertension and shortness of breath. 
Please evaluate for pulmonary embolism.

COMPARISON:  ___.

TECHNIQUE:  Contiguous axial images through the chest were performed after the
dynamic injection of IV contrast.  Coronal and sagittal reformatted images
were also obtained.  Total exam DLP equals 390.36 mGy-cm.

FINDINGS:

There is stenosis of the left subclavian vein and brachiocephalic vein with a
patent SVC resulting in multiple thoracic collateral vessels and enlarged
azygos vein.

The aorta, main pulmonary artery and heart are normal in size.  There is no
evidence for pulmonary embolism to the segmental level.  There is no
pericardial effusion.

The central tracheobronchial tree is patent.  There is bilateral dependent
atelectasis.  No pulmonary nodules or pleural effusions are seen.

The visualized upper abdomen is unremarkable.  No lytic or blastic lesions are
seen within the visualized skeleton.

IMPRESSION:  
1. No evidence for pulmonary embolism.

2. Stenosis of the left subclavian vein and bilateral brachiocephalic veins
with patency of the SVC resulting in multiple thoracic collateral vessels.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  ___ woman with new thrombocytopenia, elevated LDH
with concern for lymphoma.  Evaluate for splenomegaly or intra-abdominal
lymphadenopathy.

COMPARISON:  CT chest ___ abdominal ultrasound ___.

FINDINGS:  The liver shows no focal or textural abnormality. Doppler
assessment of the main portal vein shows patency and normal hepatopetal flow.
There is no intra- or extra-hepatic bile duct dilation.  The common duct is
not dilated measuring 4 mm. The gallbladder is normal without stones. The
visualized portions of the pancreatic head, body, and tail are normal,
although the inferior head and lateral tail are not well seen due to overlying
bowel gas. 

The spleen is borderline enlarged measuring 12.9 cm, previously 11.0 cm on
___. Two splenic hyperechoic foci are seen. The first is 1.1 x 0.9 x 0.9
cm, unchanged from prior. A second fcus measures 0.6 x 0.7 cm. These likely
represent small hemangiomas. 

The right kidney is 10.6 cm. The left kidney is 7.4 cm, though this likely
represents an under-measurement due to technique.  Innumerable cysts are seen
bilaterally, the largest measuring 3.0 cm in the right renal upper pole and
2.9 cm in the left lateral kidney. There is no hydronephrosis. The aorta is of
normal caliber throughout. Visualized portions of the IVC are normal. There is
no ascites. No sonographic evidence of enlarged retroperitoneal lymph nodes.

IMPRESSION:
1.  Borderline enlarged spleen to 12.9 cm, increased from ___.
2.  No sonographic evidence of retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy.
3.  Innumerable bilateral renal cysts.
4.  Small splenic hyperechoic foci likely represent hemangiomas.
